Renetik Android Build Notes
===========================

This file documents the exact setup that was needed to build this ffmpeg-kit
checkout successfully on this machine as it exists now.

Environment
-----------

- Machine: Apple Silicon MacBook (arm64)
- macOS: Darwin 25.x
- Repo path used for the successful build:
  `/Users/renetik/Documents/Development/renetik/ffmpeg-kit`

What Was Required
-----------------

1. Homebrew tools had to be installed:

   - `pkg-config`
   - `cmake`
   - `ninja`
   - `meson`
   - `nasm`
   - `autoconf`
   - `automake`
   - `libtool`
   - `gperf`
   - `openjdk@17`

2. Android SDK CMake had to be `3.22.1`.

   Important:
   ffmpeg-kit's Android scripts look for CMake inside
   `ANDROID_SDK_ROOT/cmake/...` before checking `PATH`.

   CMake 4 caused `cpu-features` to fail.

   The working SDK CMake was:

   `/Users/renetik/Library/Android/sdk/cmake/3.22.1/bin/cmake`

3. Android NDK had to be `25.1.8937393`.

   The current/latest NDK 29 did not work with this repo as-is because the
   scripts still rely on older NDK path/layout assumptions.

   Working NDK:

   `/tmp/android-ndk-r25b`

   with:

   `Pkg.Revision = 25.1.8937393`

4. Java had to be JDK 17.

   Working JDK:

   `/opt/homebrew/opt/openjdk@17/libexec/openjdk.jdk/Contents/Home`

5. Rosetta compatibility was still needed on Apple Silicon.

   This repo already handles that in its Android build scripts by selecting the
   `darwin-x86_64` NDK host toolchain on arm64 macOS.

Important Build Behavior
------------------------

- `src/*` contains downloaded/upstream nested repositories used by the build.
  These are not part of the top-level repo history.
- The build also generates ignored outputs under:
  - `.tmp/`
  - `prebuilt/`
  - `android/libs/`
  - `android/obj/`
  - `android/ffmpeg-kit-android-lib/build/`
- Some IDEs may still show those generated/nested-repo files even though the
  top-level repository is clean.

Recovered Working Build Variant
-------------------------------

This was the successful Android package variant recovered from the previous
build log and then rebuilt successfully:

`--enable-lame --enable-opus --enable-gpl --enable-rubberband --disable-lib-x264 --disable-lib-x265 --disable-lib-xvidcore --disable-lib-libvidstab`

Because this checkout already contained stale prebuilt/pkg-config data from a
different machine/path, the successful rebuild also forced regeneration of the
enabled dependency outputs:

`--rebuild-cpu-features --rebuild-lame --rebuild-libiconv --rebuild-libsndfile --rebuild-libsamplerate --rebuild-opus --rebuild-rubberband`

